1/13/2019

Getting to know the F-distribution

Recall that when we run an ANOVA we: 1. calculate the observed F-value from the data (ratio of explained vs. unexplained variance) 2. then compare the calculated F-value to what we would expect to find if the null hypothesis was true (by calculating the probability we would have observed that p-value under the null) 3. if the probability is lower than our cut-off (alpha) we reject the null

Because of random variability we probably expect a range of F-values when there are no real differences.

We will create a simulation and see what the distribution of expected F-values looks like under different single factor experiments.

Programming challenge #1: visualizing expected F-values

  1. simulate data from a single factor experiment with 2 levels (10 subjects per level) where there is no difference between the means
  2. run an anova on the simulated data and store the observed F-value
  3. repeat 1000 times
  4. create a histogram of F-values
  5. find the critical F-value (our 0.05 cutoff) and display it in the graph
Fvalue<-c()
for (i in seq(1:10000)){
    condition<-c(rep("A",10),rep("B",10))
    scores<-rnorm(20,8,2)
    data<-data.frame(condition,scores)
    Fvalue<-c(Fvalue,summary(aov(scores ~ condition))[[1]][["F value"]][[1]])
}

df<-data.frame(Fvalue)

ggplot(df, aes(Fvalue)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = stat(density)), bins = 100) +
   ylab("Density") +
  xlab("F-values") +
  stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
    args = list(mean = mean(Fvalue), sd = sd(Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'red'
  ) +
 theme_minimal() +
 geom_vline(xintercept = quantile(df$Fvalue, 0.95))

quantile(df$Fvalue, 0.95)
##      95%
## 4.426723
qf(.95, df1=1, df2=18)
## [1] 4.413873

Programming challenge #2

  1. Repeat the above simulation with 4, 20, and 100 subjects per group (1000 simulations each)
  2. Create a graph that displays all four F-distributions
  3. What happens to the critical F-value as the number of subjects (denominator degrees of freedom) increases?
Fvalue<-c()
for(n in c(8,40,200)){
    for (i in seq(1:1000)){
    condition<-c(rep("A",n/2),rep("B",n/2))
    scores<-rnorm(n,8,2)
    data<-data.frame(condition,scores)

    Fvalue<-c(Fvalue,summary(aov(scores ~ condition))[[1]][["F value"]][[1]])
    }
}


df<-data.frame(Fvalue)
df$N <- c(rep("4",1000),
          rep("20",1000),
          rep("100",1000)
)


ggplot(df, aes(Fvalue)) +
  #geom_histogram(aes(y = stat(density)), bins = 100) +
  ylab("Density") +
  xlab("F-values") +
  xlim(0, 10) +
  stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
    args = list(mean = mean(df[df$N == "4",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$N == "4",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'red'
  ) +
    stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
   args = list(mean = mean(df[df$N == "20",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$N == "20",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'blue'
  ) +
     stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
   args = list(mean = mean(df[df$N == "100",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$N == "100",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'green'
  ) +
 theme_minimal() +
 geom_vline(colour = "red", xintercept = quantile(df[df$N == "4",]$Fvalue,0.95))+
 geom_vline(colour = "blue", xintercept = quantile(df[df$N == "20",]$Fvalue,0.95))+
 geom_vline(colour = "green", xintercept = quantile(df[df$N == "100",]$Fvalue,0.95))

quantile(df[df$N == "4",]$Fvalue,0.95)
##      95%
## 5.122258
qf(.95, df1=1, df2=6)
## [1] 5.987378
quantile(df[df$N == "20",]$Fvalue,0.95)
##      95%
## 4.193376
qf(.95, df1=1, df2=18)
## [1] 4.413873
quantile(df[df$N == "100",]$Fvalue,0.95)
##      95%
## 3.800023
qf(.95, df1=1, df2=198)
## [1] 3.888853

Programming challenge #3

  1. Simulate (as above) experiments with 2, 3, and 4 levels.
  2. Create a graph that displays all four F-distributions
  3. What happens to the critical F-value as the number of levels (numerator degrees of freedom) increases
Fvalue<-c()
for(n in c(2,3,4)){
    for (i in seq(1:1000)){
    condition<-c(rep("A",10),rep("B",10), rep("C",10),rep("D",10))
    condition<-condition[1:(n*10)]
    scores<-rnorm(10*n,8,2)
    data<-data.frame(condition,scores)

    Fvalue<-c(Fvalue,summary(aov(scores ~ condition))[[1]][["F value"]][[1]])
    }
}


df<-data.frame(Fvalue)
df$levels <- c(rep("2",1000),
          rep("3",1000),
          rep("4",1000)
)


ggplot(df, aes(Fvalue)) +
  #geom_histogram(aes(y = stat(density)), bins = 100) +
  ylab("Density") +
  xlab("F-values") +
  xlim(0, 10) +
  stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
    args = list(mean = mean(df[df$levels == "2",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$levels == "2",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'red'
  ) +
    stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
   args = list(mean = mean(df[df$levels == "3",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$levels == "3",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'blue'
  ) +
     stat_function(
    fun = dnorm,
   args = list(mean = mean(df[df$levels == "4",]$Fvalue), sd = sd(df[df$levels == "4",]$Fvalue)),
    lwd = 1,
    col = 'green'
  ) +
 theme_minimal() +
 geom_vline(colour = "red", xintercept = quantile(df[df$levels == "2",]$Fvalue,0.95))+
 geom_vline(colour = "blue", xintercept = quantile(df[df$levels == "3",]$Fvalue,0.95))+
 geom_vline(colour = "green", xintercept = quantile(df[df$levels == "4",]$Fvalue,0.95))
